e":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastric ulcer","Gastric erosion","Gastric polyp","Normal gastric mucosa","Gastric adenocarcinoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph gives a view of the mid-body of the stomach, with the pylorus just visible in the distance. Two \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric ulcers\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen, one on the anterior aspect of the stomach and the other on the posterior aspect. They are well-demarcated mucosal defects with slightly rolled edges and a white/yellow base. This appearance differs from a \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric erosion\u003C/strong\u003E which is more superficial and does not extend beyond the muscularis mucosa (Image 1). A \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric polyp\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a raised lesion protruding into the lumen (Image 2). \u003Cstrong\u003ENormal gastric mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E has a smooth, pink appearance with visible mucosal folds. This is visible around the two ulcers in the photograph. \u003Cstrong\u003EGastric adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as an irregular, friable mass with concerning features such as nodularity or irregular borders (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastric ulcers appear as well-demarcated mucosal defects with a white/yellow base on endoscopy","Key endoscopic features of gastric ulcers include raised edges, depth, and a clearly visible ulcer base"],"references":["\u0022Esophagogastroduodenoscopy Image of gastric ulcers in antrum\u0022 by Med_Chaos  is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Endoscopic_images_of_gastric_ulcers#/media/File:Gastric_Ulcer_Antrum.jpg","Woolf A, Rose R. Gastric Ulcer. [Updated 2023 Nov 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537128/","Dixon MF. Pathology of Gastritis and 